I Pt 3}}\n* {{YouTube|M6z-fZwpmME|The Battle of China OWI Pt 4}}\n* {{YouTube|VKHk6eepm0E|The Battle of China OWI Pt 5}}\n* {{YouTube|L_zntg-eFF0|The Battle of China OWI Pt 6}}\n* {{YouTube|k0hZiD5Uk5I|The Battle of China OWI Pt 7}}\n\n{{World War II}}\n{{World War II history by nation}}\n{{JapanEmpireNavbox}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Second Sino-Japanese War| ]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Japan]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the Republic of China]]\n[[Category:Anti-Chinese violence in Asia]]\n[[Category:Anti-Japanese sentiment in China]]\n[[Category:China\u2013Japan military relations]]\n[[Category:Invasions by Japan]]\n[[Category:Military history of China during World War II|*]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Republic of China]]\n[[Category:Pacific theatre of World War II]]\n[[Category:Republic of China (1912\u20131949)]]\n[[Category:Religion-based wars]]\n[[Category:Tunnel warfare]]\n[[Category:1930s in China]]\n[[Category:1940s in China]]\n[[Category:Invasions of China]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:1930s in Japan]]\n[[Category:1940s in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:1930s conflicts]]\n[[Category:1940s conflicts]]\n", "name_user": "Havsj\u00f6", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Sino-Japanese_War"}
{"title_page": "Henry of Sandomierz", "text_new": "{{ infobox nobility\n| name         = Henry\n| title        = Duke of Sandomierz\n| image        = Insigne Polonicum.svg \n| image_size   = 150px\n| caption      = Coat-of-arms of Piast of Poland\n| noble family = [[Piast dynasty]]\n| father       = Boles\u0142aw III Wrymouth]]\n| mother       = [[Salomea of Berg]]\n| spouse       = \n| issue        = \n| birth_date   = ca. 1131\n| birth_place  = \n| death_date   = 18 October 1166\n| death_place  = \n}}\n\n'''Henry of Sandomierz''' ({{lang-pl|'''Henryk Sandomierski'''}}) (ca. 1131 \u2013 18 October 1166) was a Duke of [[Sandomierz]] since 1138 (titulary) or 1146 (formally) until his death.\n\nHe was the fifth but third surviving son of [[Boles\u0142aw III Wrymouth]], Duke of Poland, by his second wife [[Salomea of Berg|Salomea]], daughter of [[Henry, Count of Berg]], from whom he received his name.\n\n==Life==\nAccording to [[Testament of Boles\u0142aw III Krzywousty|the Testament of his father]], Henry inherited the Duchy of [[Sandomierz]], which was at that time in the [[Seniorate Province]] of his eldest half-brother and High Duke, [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw II the Exile|W\u0142adys\u0142aw II]]. Because at the time of Boles\u0142aw III's death he was still a minor (1138) the Duchy remained in the Seniorate until he reached the proper age, when W\u0142adys\u0142aw had to given him. But Henry could take formal possession of Sandomierz only when the High Duke was deposed and exiled, in 1146.\n\nAs ruler of Sandomierz, Henry appears only on the occasion of the Act of Foundation of a Church in his land. His Ducal title was rarely mentioned by the chronicles, who called him ''a son of Boles\u0142aw III Wrymouth'' or ''brother of [[Boles\u0142aw IV the Curly]]''. Some historians (for example [[M. G\u0142adysz]] and [[D. Guttner]]) advance a hypothesis that he was the \u201cKing of the Poles\u201d mentioned by the Greek chronicler [[John Kinnamos]]. If the theory were to be correct, Henry would have been the commander of the Polish contingent in the [[Second Crusade]] in 1147. This possible incursion in the Crusades was short (if really occur), because in 1149, together with his older brother Boles\u0142aw IV, he took part in a military expedition in [[Kiev]] to support the Grand Prince [[Iziaslav II of Kiev|Iziaslav II]].\n\nThe first and maybe the most famous of all Sandomierz's Dukes, Henry certainly ventured to the [[Holy Land]] in 1153-1154 (a number of Polish annals reported it under the year 1154 as did [[Jan D\u0142ugosz]] in his Annals) and took part in the Crusade under the command of King [[Baldwin III of Jerusalem]]. Henry close affiliation to crusading resulted in the establishment of a commandery of the [[Hospitallers]] (between 1154 and 1166) in [[Stara Zago\u015b\u0107|Zago\u015b\u0107]].\n\nAfter returning to Poland with an air of holiness, Henry, together with his brothers, organized a Crusade against the pagan [[Old Prussians|Prussians]]. The military expedition, under the command of Boles\u0142aw IV and Henry, launched in the second half of 1166. He never return home.\n\nAccording to the chronicles, Henry was killed in battle against the Prussians, and this fact was without doubts. The date of his death, 18 October 1166, was known through indirect sources. However, there is a legend, where Henry apparently was killed in the current [[W\u0105brze\u017ano County]], probably in the vicinity of [[Nielub]] or [[Or\u0142owo, W\u0105brze\u017ano County|Or\u0142owo]], close to the [[Wieczno]] Lake.\n\nHenry never married and hence left no legitimate offspring. In his will, he left his Duchy to his youngest brother, [[Kazimierz II the Just]], who until that time, he remained without lands. These last will was done only partially. The destiny of the Duchy of Sandomierz could be shown in a document dated 31 December 1167:\n\n:''In the year 1166 in Poland during the reign of Princes Boles\u0142aw, Mieszko and Kazimierz, their fourth brother, Prince Henry died without offspring. His district has been divided into three parts; the seat of his sovereignty, Sandomierz, was granted to Boles\u0142aw, the older brother. The same day and year, [[Mateusz (bishop)|Mateusz]], [[List of Roman Catholic Bishops of Krak\u00f3w|Bishop of Krak\u00f3w]], also died.''\n\nThe other two parts were taken by the other surviving brothers: [[Wi\u015blica]], was given to Kazimiez II, and the rest to [[Mieszko III the Old]].\n\nHis remains were probably buried in a crypt of a church in [[Wi\u015blica]], where his grave is marked by an ornamental tombstone donated by his younger brother Kazimierz II. Only in 1173, after the death of Boles\u0142aw, Kazimierz finally could take the title of Duke of Sandomierz.\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Henry of Sandomierz'''\n|2= 2. [[Boles\u0142aw III Wrymouth]]\n|3= 3. [[Salomea of Berg]]\n\n|4= 4. [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw I Herman]]\n|5= 5. [[Judith of Bohemia]]\n|6= 6. [[Henry, Count of Berg]]\n|7= 7. Adelaide of Mochental\n\n|8= 8. [[Casimir I the Restorer]]\n|9= 9. [[Maria Dobroniega of Kiev]]\n|10= 10. [[Vratislaus II of Bohemia]]\n|11= 11. [[Adelaide of Hungary]]\n|12= 12. Poppo, Count of Berg\n|13= 13. Sophia\n|14= 14. Diepold II, Count of Cham\n|15= 15. Liutgarde of Z\u00e4hringen\n\n|16= 16. [[Mieszko II Lambert]]\n|17= 17. [[Richeza of Lotharingia]]\n\n|18= 18. [[Vladimir I of Kiev]]\n|19=\n\n|20= 20. [[Bretislaus I, Duke of Bohemia]]\n|21= 21. [[Judith of Schweinfurt]]\n\n|22= 22. [[Andrew I of Hungary]]\n|23= 23. [[Anastasia of Kiev]]\n\n|24= \n|25=\n\n|26= \n|27=\n\n|28= 28. Diepold I, Margrave of Cham-Vohburg \n|29=\n\n|30= 30. [[Berthold II, Duke of Carinthia]]\n|31= \n}}\n\n==References==\n*Balzer, O. Genealogia Piast\u00f3w, Krak\u00f3w, 1895.\n*G\u0142adysz, M. Zapomniani krzy\u017cowcy, Warszawa, 2006.\n*Guttner, D. \"Henryk of Sandomierz.\" [in:] The Crusades: An Encyclopedia, Santa Barbara, 2006.\n*Jasi\u0144ski, K. Rodow\u00f3d pierwszych Piast\u00f3w, Warszawa, 1992.\n*Mitkowski, J. \"Henryk ksi\u0105\u017c\u0119 sandomierski.\" [in:] Polski S\u0142ownik Biograficzny, vol. 9, Wroc\u0142aw, 1960-1961.\n* [[D. von G\u00fcttner-Sporzy\u0144ski]], ''Poland, Holy War, and the Piast Monarchy, 1100-1230'', Brepols, Turnhout, 2014.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.academia.edu/399540/Recent_Issues_in_Polish_Historiography_of_the_Crusades Receint Issues in Polish Historiography of the Crusades]\n* [https://www.academia.edu/5220373/The_archetypal_crusader_Henry_of_Sandomierz_the_second_youngest_son_of_Boleslaw_III The archetypal crusader: Henry of Sandomierz, the second youngest son of Boles\u0142aw III of Poland]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Piast Dynasty]]||ca. 1131|18 October|1166|}}\n{{s-bef|before=new creation}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Sandomierz|Duke of Sandomierz]]|years=1138/46&ndash;1166}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Boles\u0142aw IV the Curly]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n<!--Categories-->\n[[Category:12th-century births]]\n[[Category:1166 deaths]]\n[[Category:Dukes of Sandomierz]]\n[[Category:Polish Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:12th-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Polish military personnel killed in action]]\n[[Category:Christians of the Prussian Crusade]]\n[[Category:12th-century Polish people]]\n[[Category:Monarchs killed in action]]\n", "text_old": "{{ infobox nobility\n| name         = Henry\n| title        = Duke of Sandomierz\n| image        = Insigne Polonicum.svg \n| image_size   = 150px\n| caption      = Coat-of-arms of Piast of Poland\n| noble family = [[Silesian Piasts]]\n| father       = Boles\u0142aw III Wrymouth]]\n| mother       = [[Salomea of Berg]]\n| spouse       = \n| issue        = \n| birth_date   = ca. 1131\n| birth_place  = \n| death_date   = 18 October 1166\n| death_place  = \n}}\n\n'''Henry of Sandomierz''' ({{lang-pl|'''Henryk Sandomierski'''}}) (ca. 1131 \u2013 18 October 1166) was a Duke of [[Sandomierz]] since 1138 (titulary) or 1146 (formally) until his death.\n\nHe was the fifth but third surviving son of [[Boles\u0142aw III Wrymouth]], Duke of Poland, by his second wife [[Salomea of Berg|Salomea]], daughter of [[Henry, Count of Berg]], from whom he received his name.\n\n==Life==\nAccording to [[Testament of Boles\u0142aw III Krzywousty|the Testament of his father]], Henry inherited the Duchy of [[Sandomierz]], which was at that time in the [[Seniorate Province]] of his eldest half-brother and High Duke, [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw II the Exile|W\u0142adys\u0142aw II]]. Because at the time of Boles\u0142aw III's death he was still a minor (1138) the Duchy remained in the Seniorate until he reached the proper age, when W\u0142adys\u0142aw had to given him. But Henry could take formal possession of Sandomierz only when the High Duke was deposed and exiled, in 1146.\n\nAs ruler of Sandomierz, Henry appears only on the occasion of the Act of Foundation of a Church in his land. His Ducal title was rarely mentioned by the chronicles, who called him ''a son of Boles\u0142aw III Wrymouth'' or ''brother of [[Boles\u0142aw IV the Curly]]''. Some historians (for example [[M. G\u0142adysz]] and [[D. Guttner]]) advance a hypothesis that he was the \u201cKing of the Poles\u201d mentioned by the Greek chronicler [[John Kinnamos]]. If the theory were to be correct, Henry would have been the commander of the Polish contingent in the [[Second Crusade]] in 1147. This possible incursion in the Crusades was short (if really occur), because in 1149, together with his older brother Boles\u0142aw IV, he took part in a military expedition in [[Kiev]] to support the Grand Prince [[Iziaslav II of Kiev|Iziaslav II]].\n\nThe first and maybe the most famous of all Sandomierz's Dukes, Henry certainly ventured to the [[Holy Land]] in 1153-1154 (a number of Polish annals reported it under the year 1154 as did [[Jan D\u0142ugosz]] in his Annals) and took part in the Crusade under the command of King [[Baldwin III of Jerusalem]]. Henry close affiliation to crusading resulted in the establishment of a commandery of the [[Hospitallers]] (between 1154 and 1166) in [[Stara Zago\u015b\u0107|Zago\u015b\u0107]].\n\nAfter returning to Poland with an air of holiness, Henry, together with his brothers, organized a Crusade against the pagan [[Old Prussians|Prussians]]. The military expedition, under the command of Boles\u0142aw IV and Henry, launched in the second half of 1166. He never return home.\n\nAccording to the chronicles, Henry was killed in battle against the Prussians, and this fact was without doubts. The date of his death, 18 October 1166, was known through indirect sources. However, there is a legend, where Henry apparently was killed in the current [[W\u0105brze\u017ano County]], probably in the vicinity of [[Nielub]] or [[Or\u0142owo, W\u0105brze\u017ano County|Or\u0142owo]], close to the [[Wieczno]] Lake.\n\nHenry never married and hence left no legitimate offspring. In his will, he left his Duchy to his youngest brother, [[Kazimierz II the Just]], who until that time, he remained without lands. These last will was done only partially. The destiny of the Duchy of Sandomierz could be shown in a document dated 31 December 1167:\n\n:''In the year 1166 in Poland during the reign of Princes Boles\u0142aw, Mieszko and Kazimierz, their fourth brother, Prince Henry died without offspring. His district has been divided into three parts; the seat of his sovereignty, Sandomierz, was granted to Boles\u0142aw, the older brother. The same day and year, [[Mateusz (bishop)|Mateusz]], [[List of Roman Catholic Bishops of Krak\u00f3w|Bishop of Krak\u00f3w]], also died.''\n\nThe other two parts were taken by the other surviving brothers: [[Wi\u015blica]], was given to Kazimiez II, and the rest to [[Mieszko III the Old]].\n\nHis remains were probably buried in a crypt of a church in [[Wi\u015blica]], where his grave is marked by an ornamental tombstone donated by his younger brother Kazimierz II. Only in 1173, after the death of Boles\u0142aw, Kazimierz finally could take the title of Duke of Sandomierz.\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Henry of Sandomierz'''\n|2= 2. [[Boles\u0142aw III Wrymouth]]\n|3= 3. [[Salomea of Berg]]\n\n|4= 4. [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw I Herman]]\n|5= 5. [[Judith of Bohemia]]\n|6= 6. [[Henry, Count of Berg]]\n|7= 7. Adelaide of Mochental\n\n|8= 8. [[Casimir I the Restorer]]\n|9= 9. [[Maria Dobroniega of Kiev]]\n|10= 10. [[Vratislaus II of Bohemia]]\n|11= 11. [[Adelaide of Hungary]]\n|12= 12. Poppo, Count of Berg\n|13= 13. Sophia\n|14= 14. Diepold II, Count of Cham\n|15= 15. Liutgarde of Z\u00e4hringen\n\n|16= 16. [[Mieszko II Lambert]]\n|17= 17. [[Richeza of Lotharingia]]\n\n|18= 18. [[Vladimir I of Kiev]]\n|19=\n\n|20= 20. [[Bretislaus I, Duke of Bohemia]]\n|21= 21. [[Judith of Schweinfurt]]\n\n|22= 22. [[Andrew I of Hungary]]\n|23= 23. [[Anastasia of Kiev]]\n\n|24= \n|25=\n\n|26= \n|27=\n\n|28= 28. Diepold I, Margrave of Cham-Vohburg \n|29=\n\n|30= 30. [[Berthold II, Duke of Carinthia]]\n|31= \n}}\n\n==References==\n*Balzer, O. Genealogia Piast\u00f3w, Krak\u00f3w, 1895.\n*G\u0142adysz, M. Zapomniani krzy\u017cowcy, Warszawa, 2006.\n*Guttner, D. \"Henryk of Sandomierz.\" [in:] The Crusades: An Encyclopedia, Santa Barbara, 2006.\n*Jasi\u0144ski, K. Rodow\u00f3d pierwszych Piast\u00f3w, Warszawa, 1992.\n*Mitkowski, J. \"Henryk ksi\u0105\u017c\u0119 sandomierski.\" [in:] Polski S\u0142ownik Biograficzny, vol. 9, Wroc\u0142aw, 1960-1961.\n* [[D. von G\u00fcttner-Sporzy\u0144ski]], ''Poland, Holy War, and the Piast Monarchy, 1100-1230'', Brepols, Turnhout, 2014.\n\n==External links==\n* [